Neutrons are produced by an intense pulsed
beam of 20 GeV/c protons impinging on a massive
cylindrical Pb target. Repetition rate in multiples of
1.2 s and a proton pulse width of 7 ns. 300 neutrons
are produced per proton, resulting in a total of 2E+15
neutrons per pulse. The neutron beam is shaped by
collimators at 137 and 178 m from spallation target.

x4freetext: Data were received from P.Zugec 2 Feb.2014.
The experimental data were fitted by a multilevel
R-matrix code SAMMY, which accounts for the resolution
function of the neutron beam, Doppler broadening of
self-shielding effects. The reasonable fit for energies
up to 10 keV was obtained by considering two resonances
with negative energy. The energy and neutron width of
the two resonances were fixed at the value adopted from
the ENDF/B-VII.1,while the capture width was left free.
